# Timebox {#timebox}

4–6 hours.

# Goal {#goal}

Build a small LLM-powered chat task tracker that turns a stream of chat messages into structured tasks, supports completing tasks and attaching free-text details, and provides a simple read-only web UI to view tasks.

This test is designed to evaluate:

* Practical product engineering with LLMs (prompting, tool/function calling, guardrails)  
* Backend fundamentals (idempotency, persistence, correctness)  
* End-to-end wiring (chat input → LLM → actions → storage → web view)

# Functional Requirements {#functional-requirements}

## R1 — Create one or several tasks from user input {#r1-—-create-one-or-several-tasks-from-user-input}

From a single user message, the system must be able to create one or multiple tasks.

* The exact syntax is intentionally open-ended: the LLM decides whether the message implies 1 task, multiple tasks, or none.  
* The system must reply in chat with a clear summary of what was created.

## R2 — Complete tasks from user input {#r2-—-complete-tasks-from-user-input}

From a user message, the system must be able to mark tasks as completed.

* The user may reference tasks by partial title, approximate wording, or index.  
* The LLM decides which task(s) the user intends (assuming a small task set).  
* If the intent is unclear, the assistant should ask a short clarifying question.

## R3 — Attach free-text details to tasks {#r3-—-attach-free-text-details-to-tasks}

From a user message, the system must be able to append free-text details to a task.

* These details may represent notes, updates, “commit-like” entries, or any operational context.  
* The LLM decides which task the detail belongs to.

# Interfaces {#interfaces}

## Chat interface {#chat-interface}

Provide a way to send messages and display replies.

* “Ugly but functional” is fine.  
* Acceptable: minimal web page, CLI, or HTTP endpoint with a small client.

## Web interface {#web-interface}

Provide a simple read-only web UI to view tasks.

* Must include a task list.  
* Must include a task detail view showing attached details.  
* Good-to-have: allow completing tasks from the web UI.

# System Behavior Requirements {#system-behavior-requirements}

## S1 — LLM-powered interpretation {#s1-—-llm-powered-interpretation}

All user-facing interpretation (create/complete/attach detail) must be LLM-powered.

* The implementation may use tool/function calling, structured outputs, or a planner/executor pattern.  
* Rule-based parsing is allowed only as an optimization or fallback; the primary behavior should come from the LLM.

## S2 — Idempotency / duplicates {#s2-—-idempotency-/-duplicates}

The system must not duplicate effects when the same/similar inbound message is processed multiple times.

* If the same inbound message is received twice, it must not create duplicate tasks or duplicate details.  
* The design should explain how idempotency is achieved.  
* Include at least one test or demo script that proves idempotency.

## S3 — Small task-set assumption {#s3-—-small-task-set-assumption}

Assume a small number of tasks (e.g., dozens, not thousands).

* This enables LLM inference based on the current task list.  
* You may choose how much task context to provide to the LLM.

## S4 — Conversational context {#s4-—-conversational-context}

The system may keep prior messages in the LLM context window to improve interpretation.

* You decide how to store and retrieve conversation history.  
* You decide how to prevent runaway prompt growth.

## S5 — System reset {#s5-—-system-reset}

Provide a simple way to reset the system state to a clean slate to simplify testing.

Acceptable approaches include:

* a CLI command (e.g. `pnpm reset`)  
* HTTP endpoint (e.g. `POST /admin/reset`)  
* A “reset” chat command

# Tech Constraints {#tech-constraints}

* The backend must be TypeScript/Node.  
* Storage: any persistent DB choice (SQLite/Postgres/etc.) is acceptable.  
* Any TS backend framework is acceptable.  
* Any library/ framework for LLM or chat interactions are allowed  
* Any LLM model that will do the job for the chat-based interaction\*

**\*I’d look at LLM models with a generous free tier: Grok, Gemini, perhaps OpenRouter.**

# Deliverables {#deliverables}

* A repo with setup and run instructions.  
* A short README covering:  
  * Architecture overview (components and boundaries)  
  * How the LLM is used (prompting approach, tool/function schema if used)  
  * Idempotency approach (and why it works)  
  * Key tradeoffs and what you’d improve next  
* A runnable demo path:  
  * Start backend \+ UI  
  * Show 3 short demo interactions:  
    1. Create multiple tasks from one message  
    2. Complete a task from a natural instruction  
    3. Attach a detail to a task  
  * Demonstrate idempotency requirement